00:07:17.430 --> 00:07:21.090
They were really struggling just
to have fairness in the system.

00:07:21.090 --> 00:07:25.440
And that's why I chose that
as the title of my talk.

00:07:25.440 --> 00:07:32.530
It was a legislative battle to try
to remove race and national origins

00:07:32.530 --> 00:07:37.730
from the criteria that we
use to admit immigrants.

00:07:37.730 --> 00:07:41.760
And I have a really long lecture
that you're not going to hear.

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:45.880
You can applaud now.

00:07:45.880 --> 00:07:53.460
[Laughs]. And I've reduced my
research into three concepts.

00:07:53.460 --> 00:07:55.350
And the first of the three concepts

00:07:55.350 --> 00:07:58.020
of course is race and
national origins.

00:07:58.020 --> 00:08:02.290
Because that's the
subject of my research.

00:08:02.290 --> 00:08:05.600
But you can't talk about these
in the context of immigration

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:12.010
without also dealing with two
other very fundamental concepts.

00:08:12.010 --> 00:08:16.190
One that I'm calling the
ideology of the deserving.

00:08:16.190 --> 00:08:20.670
That's the selection process,
the selectivity in immigration.

00:08:20.670 --> 00:08:25.010
And the other is what I'm
calling apportionment politics

00:08:25.010 --> 00:08:27.310
or power politics.

00:08:29.560 --> 00:08:31.820
There we go.

00:08:31.820 --> 00:08:37.190 position:56%
When we talk about race and
national origins, when we're talking

00:08:37.190 --> 00:08:41.460
about the early 20th
century, the concept of race

00:08:41.460 --> 00:08:43.670
and national origins
was very different

00:08:43.670 --> 00:08:47.720
from what we would have
today, the 21st century view.

00:08:47.720 --> 00:08:51.310
The government had over
39 different categories

00:08:51.310 --> 00:08:53.190
of race and national origin.

00:08:53.190 --> 00:08:56.160
And I chose this cartoon from
the library's collections.

00:08:56.160 --> 00:09:00.340
It's by the famous cartoonist
Thomas Nass from Harper's Weekly.

00:09:00.340 --> 00:09:02.600
And Nass did it right
after the passage

00:09:02.600 --> 00:09:05.020
of the Chinese exclusion laws.

00:09:05.020 --> 00:09:10.050
And there's two points that I
want to make about this cartoon.

00:09:10.050 --> 00:09:14.550
Because they illustrate
fundamental points of my talk.

00:09:14.550 --> 00:09:16.910
The first one is that it's talking

00:09:16.910 --> 00:09:20.580
about what color will
be tabooed next.

00:09:20.580 --> 00:09:24.900
It's an open acknowledgement
that there was a perception

00:09:24.900 --> 00:09:27.110
that the immigration
law that was passed

00:09:27.110 --> 00:09:30.540
in the Chinese exclusion
laws were fundamentally based

00:09:30.540 --> 00:09:32.460
on color and race.

00:09:32.460 --> 00:09:38.920
But it also shows if you look at
the depiction of Pat the Irishman,

00:09:38.920 --> 00:09:42.290
it's not exactly the most
favorable depiction of the Irish.

00:09:42.290 --> 00:09:45.110
He has a monkey-like quality.

00:09:45.110 --> 00:09:49.080
And Fritz, the German in the
cartoon, has thick glasses

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:53.070
and is also you might
say racially stereotyped

00:09:53.070 --> 00:09:57.520
or ethnically stereotyped
in this cartoon.

00:09:57.520 --> 00:10:04.140 position:56%
So that's the first point, is to get
the sense of how tribal the views

00:10:04.140 --> 00:10:08.980
on race and nationality were in the
late 19th and early 20th century.

00:10:08.980 --> 00:10:14.430
They weren't just black,
white, Asian, Indian.

00:10:14.430 --> 00:10:19.040
They were much more specific
in how they viewed people.

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:22.430
The second point, and this
gets to the selectivity,

00:10:22.430 --> 00:10:25.690
some might say class element
that I'm talking about.

00:10:25.690 --> 00:10:27.580
It's harder to see in the cartoon,

00:10:27.580 --> 00:10:33.840
but it points out that Chinese
laborers shall not come.

00:10:33.840 --> 00:10:38.490
And the Chinese exclusion acts
are wonderful illustration

00:10:38.490 --> 00:10:42.860
of the overlay of class
in selectivity

00:10:42.860 --> 00:10:45.530
on race-based admissions.

00:10:45.530 --> 00:10:50.850
Because the Chinese exclusions
laws excluded Chinese laborers.

00:10:50.850 --> 00:10:53.930
But if you go through
the congressional record,

00:10:53.930 --> 00:10:55.890
when they talked about
the legislation,

00:10:55.890 --> 00:10:57.920
they wanted to get
Chinese merchants.

00:10:57.920 --> 00:11:00.380
They wanted the wealthy
elite Chinese.

00:11:00.380 --> 00:11:02.340
It was the laborers
they didn't want.

00:11:02.340 --> 00:11:06.810
So there's no question that they
were aimed at racial exclusion,

00:11:06.810 --> 00:11:10.880
but the overlay of class
was most certainly present

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:16.480
from the earliest days
of these exclusion laws.

00:11:16.480 --> 00:11:20.890
Now the other way that
you see the selectivity,

00:11:20.890 --> 00:11:28.430
and I chose this classic picture
that Siglex took from first class,

00:11:28.430 --> 00:11:33.150
looking at the immigrants coming
on the passage across the Atlantic,

00:11:33.150 --> 00:11:37.070
was that there was a range
of different people who came

00:11:37.070 --> 00:11:39.400
as immigrants to the United States.

00:11:39.400 --> 00:11:44.570
But there was a concern
about what groups came in.

00:11:44.570 --> 00:11:50.770
And I stand on the shoulders
of the two people that --

00:11:50.770 --> 00:11:54.780
Marta Tienda and Susan Martin,
who were introduced at the onset

00:11:54.780 --> 00:11:56.480
and who will be talking shortly --

00:11:56.480 --> 00:11:58.200
because both of their
research points

00:11:58.200 --> 00:12:02.600
to these fundamental
elements of my research.

00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:04.650
Susan in her book A
Nation of Immigrants

00:12:04.650 --> 00:12:11.960
in 2009 developed how the selection
of immigrants were modelled

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:14.650
as either a Virginia
model, a Pennsylvania model,

00:12:14.650 --> 00:12:19.920
a Massachusetts model and how these
different concepts were interwoven

00:12:19.920 --> 00:12:24.460
throughout our history in terms
of how we selected immigrants.

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:29.480
Marta's work that I'm
stealing or building on comes

00:12:29.480 --> 00:12:33.550
from a 2002 speech she
gave when she was president

00:12:33.550 --> 00:12:36.300
of the American Sociological
Association.

00:12:36.300 --> 00:12:39.710
And that was on demography
and the social contract.

00:12:39.710 --> 00:12:43.110 position:56%
And this is where the
apportionment power politics element

00:12:43.110 --> 00:12:46.490
that I have been looking
at really comes into play.

00:12:46.490 --> 00:12:50.320
Because in that speech
which was later published,

00:12:50.320 --> 00:12:56.880 position:56%
she talks about how people are
counted, how immigrants are included

00:12:56.880 --> 00:13:03.080 position:56%
in the census, how fundamental that
is to the defining of our democracy.

00:13:03.080 --> 00:13:09.170 position:56%
The point I am taking from Professor
Tienda is that in the writing

00:13:09.170 --> 00:13:17.110 position:56%
of the 1924 Immigration Act, because
it's very clear from my reading

00:13:17.110 --> 00:13:22.940
of the materials that a lot of
the legislators were concerned

00:13:22.940 --> 00:13:28.490 position:56%
about how the wave of immigrants
was going to affect reapportionment.

00:13:28.490 --> 00:13:32.940
That they could even reapportion
Congress based on the 1924 census.

00:13:32.940 --> 00:13:36.610
Because it would have shifted the
power around the country so much.

00:13:36.610 --> 00:13:40.290
And they also, I think, I argue --

00:13:40.290 --> 00:13:43.050
one of the reasons they
did the exclusions,

00:13:43.050 --> 00:13:48.750
the national origins exclusions of
the '24 act was because they wanted

00:13:48.750 --> 00:13:53.790 position:56%
to try to have a little more control
over the distribution of power

00:13:53.790 --> 00:13:57.380
so that rural and southern
areas wanted to retain

00:13:57.380 --> 00:14:02.870
as much electoral power,
legislative power that they could.

00:14:02.870 --> 00:14:06.900
And so controlling immigration was
seen as one of the ways to do that.

00:14:06.900 --> 00:14:10.240
This slide just gives
you a quick snapshot

00:14:10.240 --> 00:14:12.970
of the features of the 1924 act.

00:14:12.970 --> 00:14:16.350
This was when Asians
were formally barred

00:14:16.350 --> 00:14:19.060
because they could naturalize.

00:14:19.060 --> 00:14:21.990
I'm not even -- we could talk
about this if you have questions,

00:14:21.990 --> 00:14:24.920
but it's pretty complex
to get into now.

00:14:24.920 --> 00:14:29.490
The eastern hemisphere was
limited to the 1890 census

00:14:29.490 --> 00:14:32.810
and this is the part of
the law that led to norther

00:14:32.810 --> 00:14:37.840 position:56%
and western Europe dominating in the
numbers and minimizing the numbers

00:14:37.840 --> 00:14:42.260
from southern and eastern Europe
because it was scaled back

00:14:42.260 --> 00:14:47.040
to go before the great wave
at the turn of the century.

00:14:47.040 --> 00:14:50.850
Also, the western hemisphere, all
the migrants from this hemisphere,

00:14:50.850 --> 00:14:54.200
were not held to any
numerical limits.

00:14:54.200 --> 00:15:00.140
But they were still held to
qualitative restrictions based

00:15:00.140 --> 00:15:03.680
on what we call in the immigration
world, the ground for exclusion.

00:15:03.680 --> 00:15:08.610 position:56%
So if you were a criminal, likely
to be indigent, or more importantly,

00:15:08.610 --> 00:15:12.040
coming to work without
proper authorization

00:15:12.040 --> 00:15:14.160
as contract labor,
you would be barred.

00:15:14.160 --> 00:15:16.820
So that was the way we
controlled migration

00:15:16.820 --> 00:15:20.520
from this hemisphere in 1924.

00:15:20.520 --> 00:15:24.840
This gives you a sense of
how that actually was playing

00:15:24.840 --> 00:15:27.200
out by the post-World War II era.

00:15:27.200 --> 00:15:32.530
And as you can see, the
allocation of visas to northern

00:15:32.530 --> 00:15:37.920
and western Europe was much
greater than their actual usage.

00:15:37.920 --> 00:15:40.940
Whereas the other parts
of the world were pressing

00:15:40.940 --> 00:15:42.970
against the numerical limits.

00:15:42.970 --> 00:15:46.840
You can also see from this figure
just how small the numbers were

00:15:46.840 --> 00:15:50.090
that could come in from these
other parts of the world.

00:15:50.090 --> 00:15:53.150
Now initially in the
postwar period, those who --

00:15:53.150 --> 00:15:58.260 position:56%
there had always been people opposed
to the national origins quotas.

00:15:58.260 --> 00:16:04.780 position:56%
Emanuel Celler, and it was his
papers that are the kind of the body

00:16:04.780 --> 00:16:08.230
of work that I have relied on
here at the Library of Congress.

00:16:08.230 --> 00:16:14.300 position:56%
Emanuel Celler was a new congressman
who argued against the 1924 act.

00:16:14.300 --> 00:16:19.630
In 1952 he offered an amendment
as an alternative to that act.

00:16:19.630 --> 00:16:22.220
And he was chairing the
judiciary committee, by the way,

00:16:22.220 --> 00:16:24.000
when the 1965 act passed.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.230
So this man, he was
from New York City.

00:16:27.230 --> 00:16:32.520
He spent his entire career
fighting against race

00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:35.520
and national origins admissions.

00:16:35.520 --> 00:16:37.960
They thought originally
after the war

00:16:37.960 --> 00:16:41.540
that they could get rid
of the national origins.

00:16:41.540 --> 00:16:43.060
That it was the right time.

00:16:43.060 --> 00:16:44.480
We were coming out of World War II.

00:16:44.480 --> 00:16:49.600
The public diplomacy aspects of
having national origins were seen

00:16:49.600 --> 00:16:53.490
as a liability when we dealt with
other countries around the world.

00:16:53.490 --> 00:16:55.100
The economy was roaring.

00:16:55.100 --> 00:16:57.820
We had a full employment economy.

00:16:57.820 --> 00:17:01.770
We were sending marshal
plan money to Europe.

00:17:01.770 --> 00:17:04.860
And it looked like a good time.

00:17:04.860 --> 00:17:08.090
However, even with the displaced
persons after World War II,

00:17:08.090 --> 00:17:13.140
it was very clear the public did
not support increasing immigration.

00:17:13.140 --> 00:17:18.110
And when Congress was trying
to deal with displaced persons,

00:17:18.110 --> 00:17:21.370
they were still wedded
in that process

00:17:21.370 --> 00:17:24.330
to the national origins
quotas in terms

00:17:24.330 --> 00:17:28.050
of how they responded to refugees.

00:17:28.050 --> 00:17:32.590
So in 1952, Congress
took up the McCarran Act.

00:17:32.590 --> 00:17:36.070
And I want to just
read some quotes to you

00:17:36.070 --> 00:17:40.380
to give you a flavor for the times.

00:17:40.380 --> 00:17:45.120
Because I must admit, when
I was doing my research some

00:17:45.120 --> 00:17:49.550
of these things surprised me and I
didn't think I would be surprised

00:17:49.550 --> 00:17:51.800
at this point in my career.

00:17:51.800 --> 00:17:55.970
There was a senate
report on immigration

00:17:55.970 --> 00:17:58.710
that was almost 1,000 pages long.

00:17:58.710 --> 00:18:02.060
And it had an amazing, amazing --

00:18:02.060 --> 00:18:05.400
it drew an amazing
conclusion from my perspective.

00:18:05.400 --> 00:18:08.120
Maybe you'll share my view.

00:18:08.120 --> 00:18:11.650
The Senate report criticized
national origins quotas

00:18:11.650 --> 00:18:15.900
for not admitting the
proper mix of white people.

00:18:15.900 --> 00:18:19.280
More precisely, the report
stated, "Only about half

00:18:19.280 --> 00:18:23.540
of the anticipated proportion of
immigrants have come from northern

00:18:23.540 --> 00:18:28.010
and western Europe, while twice the
contemplated proportion have come

00:18:28.010 --> 00:18:30.730
from southern and eastern Europe."

00:18:32.850 --> 00:18:36.300
The report concluded, "As a method
of preserving the relationship

00:18:36.300 --> 00:18:40.470
between the various elements
in our white population,

00:18:40.470 --> 00:18:45.650
the national origin system
has not been effective."

00:18:45.650 --> 00:18:47.360
Interesting.

00:18:47.360 --> 00:18:49.750
McCarran also -- Senator McCarran,

00:18:49.750 --> 00:18:52.430
Patrick McCarran was a
democrat from Nevada.

00:18:52.430 --> 00:18:55.410
He was also quite concerned
about illegal immigration.

00:18:55.410 --> 00:19:00.090
And before you think
this sounds contemporary,

00:19:00.090 --> 00:19:04.900
when he did a press conference
on 5 million illegal aliens

00:19:04.900 --> 00:19:08.760
that had poured into the country,
let me give you a little more

00:19:08.760 --> 00:19:11.240
of a sense of who he
was talking about.

00:19:11.240 --> 00:19:15.400
McCarran referred to these
5 million illegal aliens

00:19:15.400 --> 00:19:20.570
as "militant communists,
Sicilian bandits, criminals,

00:19:20.570 --> 00:19:23.800
and he warned that they were
a readymade fifth column

00:19:23.800 --> 00:19:25.170
for the enemy.

00:19:25.170 --> 00:19:29.670
And potentially more dangerous
than an armed invasion."

00:19:29.670 --> 00:19:32.720
That's Pat McCarran, 1951.

00:19:32.720 --> 00:19:36.970
He was joined by Senator Herbert
O'Connor who was from Maryland,

00:19:36.970 --> 00:19:41.200
who pointed out that these
unauthorized illegal aliens

00:19:41.200 --> 00:19:42.500
as they called them were coming

00:19:42.500 --> 00:19:46.630
into the United States
from Canada and Cuba.

00:19:46.630 --> 00:19:49.030
I had to pause for that.

00:19:49.030 --> 00:19:51.040
[ Laughter ]

00:19:51.040 --> 00:19:54.780
There were alternative views at the
time and a Senator, Herbert Layman

00:19:54.780 --> 00:20:00.070
of New York, he took a
totally different tack.

00:20:00.070 --> 00:20:02.120
And he said on the senate floor,

00:20:02.120 --> 00:20:05.330
"This philosophy is a
xenophobic philosophy.

00:20:05.330 --> 00:20:07.570
It is a racist philosophy.

00:20:07.570 --> 00:20:11.640
It is a philosophy of fear,
suspicion and distrust

00:20:11.640 --> 00:20:17.000
of foreigners outside our country
and of aliens within our country.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:23.180
It is a philosophy which is plainly
prejudiced against immigration."

00:20:23.180 --> 00:20:28.530
Emanuel Celler put it this
way in debating the '52 act.

00:20:28.530 --> 00:20:30.520
He said, "What is America?

00:20:30.520 --> 00:20:33.670
It is not so much that
you were born in America.

00:20:33.670 --> 00:20:39.100
The important thing is that
America has been born in you."

00:20:39.100 --> 00:20:42.140
So these were two very
different streams struggling

00:20:42.140 --> 00:20:45.740 position:56%
for control over immigration policy.

00:20:45.740 --> 00:20:49.810
Herblock. The Library of Congress
has the Herblock collection,

00:20:49.810 --> 00:20:52.880
so that was another
great fun this year.

00:20:52.880 --> 00:20:59.140
Herblock was quite pointed in his
conclusions about the 1952 act.

00:20:59.140 --> 00:21:03.440
And he ran this cartoon
shortly before Harry Truman,

00:21:03.440 --> 00:21:05.140
President Harry Truman
vetoed the act.

00:21:05.140 --> 00:21:09.180
And I want to just do one quick
excerpt from Truman's veto,

00:21:09.180 --> 00:21:13.210
again to give you a
flavor of the 1950's.

00:21:13.210 --> 00:21:17.310
"In no other realm of our
national life are we so hampered

00:21:17.310 --> 00:21:23.540 position:56%
and stultified by the dead hand of
the past, the dead hand of the past,

00:21:23.540 --> 00:21:26.420
as we are in this field
of immigration.

00:21:26.420 --> 00:21:30.120
We do not limit our cities
to their 1920 boundaries.

00:21:30.120 --> 00:21:34.460
We do not hold corporations
to their 1920 capitalizations.

00:21:34.460 --> 00:21:39.620
We welcome progress to meet the
changing conditions in every sphere

00:21:39.620 --> 00:21:42.900
of life except in the
field of immigration.

00:21:42.900 --> 00:21:48.860
It's the time to shake off this
dead weight of past mistakes.

00:21:48.860 --> 00:21:54.450 position:56%
The time to develop a decent policy
of immigration, a fitting instrument

00:21:54.450 --> 00:21:57.490
for our foreign policy
and a true reflection

00:21:57.490 --> 00:22:01.070
of the ideals we stand
for at home and abroad."

00:22:01.070 --> 00:22:07.810
I did a fair amount of
analysis on the '52 act

00:22:07.810 --> 00:22:11.330
because I got a little too sucked
into it, considering I was supposed

00:22:11.330 --> 00:22:13.420
to be working on the 1965 act.

00:22:13.420 --> 00:22:15.520
But I wanted to point
out how this graph,

00:22:15.520 --> 00:22:18.650
which is of the Senate vote -- but
the House vote is almost identical

00:22:18.650 --> 00:22:22.840
when you do this graph -- shows
what I'm talking about in terms

00:22:22.840 --> 00:22:25.510
of apportionment politics.

00:22:25.510 --> 00:22:31.230
And the regional distribution
of power and the foreign born.

00:22:31.230 --> 00:22:36.370
And I want to point out to you are
what I would call the two deviants.

00:22:36.370 --> 00:22:40.570
The two deviants -- I shouldn't
probably say that word --

00:22:40.570 --> 00:22:43.450
but they are the Republicans
who supported Truman's veto

00:22:43.450 --> 00:22:45.530
and the Democrats who
didn't support it.

00:22:45.530 --> 00:22:48.150
These were the people that
broke with their parties.

00:22:48.150 --> 00:22:51.090
You can see that the Republicans,
and there were a sizeable number

00:22:51.090 --> 00:22:54.480
of Republicans throughout
the 1950's and '60's

00:22:54.480 --> 00:22:57.310
who supported very
strongly immigration reform.

00:22:57.310 --> 00:23:04.280
Jacob Javitz, Hugh Scott,
Kenneth Keading, Prescott Bush.

00:23:04.280 --> 00:23:05.580
A large number.

00:23:05.580 --> 00:23:09.050
And they are the ones that you see
from the high immigration states

00:23:09.050 --> 00:23:11.600
and the top immigration
states who crossed over

00:23:11.600 --> 00:23:14.770
and supported Truman's veto
of the McCarran-Walter Act.

00:23:14.770 --> 00:23:20.290
Similarly, the democrats
who voted for McCarran

00:23:20.290 --> 00:23:27.090
and supported the veto
override were from the south.

00:23:27.090 --> 00:23:30.400
And I want to point out -- I pulled
Texas and Florida out separately

00:23:30.400 --> 00:23:32.770
because they're not
low immigration states.

00:23:32.770 --> 00:23:38.280
But they were solemnly against
immigration reform at that time.

00:23:38.280 --> 00:23:45.360
And also show the dark purple in
the high column, that's Arizona.

00:23:45.360 --> 00:23:49.360 position:56%
Those are the two senators from
Arizona who were democratic senators

00:23:49.360 --> 00:23:52.310
but they supported the
McCarran-Walter Act.

00:23:52.310 --> 00:23:56.320 position:56%
So this gives you kind of a feel for
what I'm talking about when I talk

00:23:56.320 --> 00:23:58.340
about the political power

00:23:58.340 --> 00:24:02.220
and apportionment dynamic
of immigration.

00:24:02.220 --> 00:24:07.000
All through the '50's of course,
after the McCarran-Walter Act,

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:11.710
there was a lot of legislative
activity on trying to come

00:24:11.710 --> 00:24:16.850 position:56%
up with alternatives to immigration,
the current immigration law.

00:24:16.850 --> 00:24:22.210
And the Truman commission
made a series

00:24:22.210 --> 00:24:24.730
of recommendations including
increasing immigration

00:24:24.730 --> 00:24:29.120
to 250,000 a year and totally
eliminating the national origins

00:24:29.120 --> 00:24:32.350
quotas and putting
everybody under one ceiling.

00:24:32.350 --> 00:24:35.900
And that was very similar to
what Senator Herbert Layman

00:24:35.900 --> 00:24:40.040
and Hubert Humphry and Congressman
Emanuel Celler introduced in '53.

00:24:40.040 --> 00:24:42.470
President Eisenhower
also came out strongly

00:24:42.470 --> 00:24:45.530
for immigration reform in 1956.

00:24:45.530 --> 00:24:47.520
It was featured in his
state of the union.

00:24:47.520 --> 00:24:51.870
He had a proposal that while
it retained national origins,

00:24:51.870 --> 00:24:54.940
it would have substantially
increased legal immigration

00:24:54.940 --> 00:24:56.250
in the United States,

00:24:56.250 --> 00:25:03.880
thereby through that increase
addressing the suppressed treatment

00:25:03.880 --> 00:25:06.490
of southern and eastern Europe.

00:25:06.490 --> 00:25:11.030
That was how Eisenhower was
responding to the backlogs

00:25:11.030 --> 00:25:14.120
in that part of the world,
was to increase the numbers.

00:25:14.120 --> 00:25:17.720
Needless to say, those
proposals didn't go anywhere,

00:25:17.720 --> 00:25:21.950
but the new senate majority
leader, Lyndon B. Johnson,

00:25:21.950 --> 00:25:26.100 position:56%
was cooking up something on the side
with Everett Dirkson the Republican

00:25:26.100 --> 00:25:28.900
and minority leader, who
was also quite sympathetic

00:25:28.900 --> 00:25:31.480
to immigration reform
throughout this period.

00:25:31.480 --> 00:25:36.040
They came up with an amendment that
they brought to the senate floor

00:25:36.040 --> 00:25:39.750
at the very last day, next
to last day of the session.

00:25:39.750 --> 00:25:41.460
And it passed.

00:25:41.460 --> 00:25:43.700
And it was similar to the
Eisenhower, picked some things

00:25:43.700 --> 00:25:47.290
from the Eisenhower proposal
from some of the Humphry,

00:25:47.290 --> 00:25:49.030
Layman and Celler proposals.

00:25:49.030 --> 00:25:50.840
It was a compromise.

00:25:50.840 --> 00:25:53.550
This is going to sound
familiar to you.

00:25:53.550 --> 00:25:56.810
It passed the Senate
but died in the House.

00:25:56.810 --> 00:26:00.130
Very little was known
about that since it kind

00:26:00.130 --> 00:26:02.120
of disappeared from our history.

00:26:02.120 --> 00:26:04.950
In the late '50's there were
also some incremental revisions

00:26:04.950 --> 00:26:10.950
to the law that actually were
quite substantial in the long run.

00:26:10.950 --> 00:26:16.030
But really nibbling on the edges
from the broader perspective.

00:26:16.030 --> 00:26:21.680
And in the early 1960's Emanuel
Celler introduced a new bill.

00:26:21.680 --> 00:26:24.290
And his bills were getting
shorter, by the way.

00:26:24.290 --> 00:26:29.560
They started in 1953 at over 200
pages, and covered the full range

00:26:29.560 --> 00:26:31.760
of immigration reform
that you can think of,

00:26:31.760 --> 00:26:33.810
including administrative
efficiencies

00:26:33.810 --> 00:26:37.240
and naturalization reforms, changes
to the grounds for admissibility,

00:26:37.240 --> 00:26:39.980
as well as elimination
of national origins.

00:26:39.980 --> 00:26:43.530
By the end, it was
down to about 12 pages.

00:26:43.530 --> 00:26:47.370
Also new on the scene was Senator
Phil Hart from Michigan who came

00:26:47.370 --> 00:26:50.460
with a very strong record
on civil rights and labor.

00:26:50.460 --> 00:26:55.850 position:56%
And he embraced immigration reform
and introduced a very important bill

00:26:55.850 --> 00:26:59.300
that included features that
were subsequently picked

00:26:59.300 --> 00:27:02.750
up in the Kennedy administration
proposal.

00:27:02.750 --> 00:27:06.580
When I talked about
selectivity at the onset,

00:27:06.580 --> 00:27:10.030
I want to also give you
a data way to look at it.

00:27:10.030 --> 00:27:11.900
And this is not necessarily
something

00:27:11.900 --> 00:27:15.600
that the legislators
of that time looked at.

00:27:15.600 --> 00:27:17.790
And that is they set
these priorities.

00:27:17.790 --> 00:27:20.650
Half were supposed to be
high-skilled immigrants.

00:27:20.650 --> 00:27:24.920
But when you look at the pie
chart for actual admissions,

00:27:24.920 --> 00:27:28.290
you see that only 6%
were high-skilled.

00:27:28.290 --> 00:27:32.110
And the parents of US citizens,
which was supposed to be 30%,

00:27:32.110 --> 00:27:34.430
well they were 4% and so on.

00:27:34.430 --> 00:27:35.730
And it rolled down.

00:27:35.730 --> 00:27:39.840
The overwhelming proportion
of immigrants that came

00:27:39.840 --> 00:27:44.320
in under the McCarran-Walter Act
were what we call non-preference.

00:27:44.320 --> 00:27:48.360
They were largely from
northern and western Europe.

00:27:48.360 --> 00:27:53.800
And they were you know, not
coming in under the priorities

00:27:53.800 --> 00:27:55.390
that had been set by Congress.

00:27:55.390 --> 00:27:58.010
So you can see there
was already a mismatch

00:27:58.010 --> 00:28:03.410 position:56%
between what the Congress had wanted
and how it ultimately played out.

00:28:03.410 --> 00:28:09.440
Well in 1963 Senator -- well,
he had been Senator Kennedy.

00:28:09.440 --> 00:28:11.350
He had chaired the immigration
subcommittee when he was

00:28:11.350 --> 00:28:15.840
in the senate and been instrumental
in pushing for immigration reform,

00:28:15.840 --> 00:28:19.920
and was truly the champion of
the immigration reform movement

00:28:19.920 --> 00:28:21.920
in the late '50's and early '60's.

00:28:21.920 --> 00:28:24.430
He did not introduce
his administration bill

00:28:24.430 --> 00:28:26.710
until the summer of '63.

00:28:26.710 --> 00:28:30.600
And it was not nearly as
ambitious as people had expected.

00:28:30.600 --> 00:28:34.320
It did not immediately
repeal national origins.

00:28:34.320 --> 00:28:36.500
It was a phase-out over five years.

00:28:36.500 --> 00:28:38.630
It emphasized high-skilled
immigration,

00:28:38.630 --> 00:28:40.510
much like McCarran-Walter.

00:28:40.510 --> 00:28:45.260
And instead of increasing overall
immigration levels to 250,000

00:28:45.260 --> 00:28:48.690 position:56%
which had been pretty much the
standard throughout the alternatives

00:28:48.690 --> 00:28:52.560
of the 1950's, it only increased
immigration by about 10,000.

00:28:52.560 --> 00:28:55.670
And these were largely aimed
at refugee populations.

00:28:55.670 --> 00:29:00.220
So there was not to be an
increase overall in immigration.

00:29:00.220 --> 00:29:02.710
Now tragically, as we all know,

00:29:02.710 --> 00:29:07.350
President Kennedy was
assassinated in the fall of 1963.

00:29:07.350 --> 00:29:10.730
And it was very unclear what
was going to happen next.

00:29:10.730 --> 00:29:16.390
The immigration reformers
were suspicious of Johnson.

00:29:16.390 --> 00:29:19.700
He had not been seen as
someone they were close to.

00:29:19.700 --> 00:29:23.950
But similarly, the defenders of
the status quo were also suspicious

00:29:23.950 --> 00:29:28.410 position:56%
of Johnson because they had worked
with him in the Senate and they knew

00:29:28.410 --> 00:29:32.010
that they were up against
a very effective adversary

00:29:32.010 --> 00:29:34.570
in terms of getting things done.

00:29:34.570 --> 00:29:37.490
And that proved to be right.

00:29:37.490 --> 00:29:41.740 position:56%
And Johnson came up with a strategy.

00:29:41.740 --> 00:29:43.630
It was fascinating.

00:29:43.630 --> 00:29:49.620
I went to the LBJ library and went
through a lot of his materials.

00:29:49.620 --> 00:29:56.780
And a strategy to get the votes,
to get the bill through and I guess

00:29:56.780 --> 00:29:59.600
in Texas they call that
giving them the Johnson.

00:29:59.600 --> 00:30:04.660
One of the things I found in the
collections that gives you a sense

00:30:04.660 --> 00:30:08.190
of how they did it back then,
50 years ago, is Myer Feldman,

00:30:08.190 --> 00:30:10.320
who was a wonderful political
strategist who had been

00:30:10.320 --> 00:30:13.490
with Kennedy -- and Johnson
kept him on for good reason --

00:30:13.490 --> 00:30:16.490
developed all these
different targeting maps based

00:30:16.490 --> 00:30:20.290
on the populations of foreign
born where the votes would be.

00:30:20.290 --> 00:30:22.500
They used it in the '64 campaign.

00:30:22.500 --> 00:30:24.950
They also used it in '65 --

00:30:24.950 --> 00:30:28.730
much more elaborate things
that this -- to win the vote.

00:30:28.730 --> 00:30:30.420
Having detailed information

00:30:30.420 --> 00:30:35.260
about the congressional districts'
foreign born population in order

00:30:35.260 --> 00:30:38.750
to buttonhole people that
they needed to support.

00:30:38.750 --> 00:30:43.720
Now public opinion at this time
was deeply divided on immigration.

00:30:43.720 --> 00:30:46.910
And I think almost
all the polling --

00:30:46.910 --> 00:30:50.230
and I was quite fortunate
to get access to a wealth

00:30:50.230 --> 00:30:52.040
of historic polling data.

00:30:52.040 --> 00:30:55.260
The public did not support
increases in immigration.

00:30:55.260 --> 00:30:59.190
And I believe that's why, though
I have no direct evidence,

00:30:59.190 --> 00:31:04.090
I think that's why the Kennedy
drafters of the bill chose not

00:31:04.090 --> 00:31:06.420
to increase immigration
beyond 10,000.

00:31:06.420 --> 00:31:09.290
Because it was so strongly
opposed by the public.

00:31:09.290 --> 00:31:17.240
What is interesting though is how
it shifted in terms of the support

00:31:17.240 --> 00:31:19.660
from the national origin system.

00:31:19.660 --> 00:31:25.120
And Lou Harris did a
survey in May of 1965.

00:31:25.120 --> 00:31:28.540
You can see from the first
pie that the populace

00:31:28.540 --> 00:31:32.100
that they interviewed was divided
up what I would say into thirds.

00:31:32.100 --> 00:31:34.470
A third that supported, 29%

00:31:34.470 --> 00:31:36.850
that supported keeping
the country quotas.

00:31:36.850 --> 00:31:40.750
36% that supported
basing it on scales.

00:31:40.750 --> 00:31:44.790 position:56%
And then 35% that were either unsure

00:31:44.790 --> 00:31:46.800
or didn't think it
made a difference.

00:31:46.800 --> 00:31:48.900
A month later, Gallop did a survey,

00:31:48.900 --> 00:31:50.700
but they framed the questions
a little differently.

00:31:50.700 --> 00:31:55.050
So don't read a whole lot into
this as a substantial change

00:31:55.050 --> 00:31:59.150
in public opinion, though there
was a concerted public relations

00:31:59.150 --> 00:32:03.650
campaign that was kicked off
in May and June of that year.

00:32:03.650 --> 00:32:07.820
But what you can see
happening is those opposed,

00:32:07.820 --> 00:32:10.630
and Gallop said there was a
hardcore group of about a third

00:32:10.630 --> 00:32:15.490
of the population -- because they
did much more detailed analysis --

00:32:15.490 --> 00:32:21.360
that opposed increasing immigration
and also supported the race

00:32:21.360 --> 00:32:24.550
and national origins-based
exclusion.

00:32:24.550 --> 00:32:27.910
What started happening
though was the shifting away

00:32:27.910 --> 00:32:29.570
of the no opinions.

00:32:29.570 --> 00:32:34.790
More of the undecided no
opinions were coming in support

00:32:34.790 --> 00:32:42.660
of basing the admissions on merit,
rather than country of birth.

00:32:42.660 --> 00:32:46.450
Well there were still a
lot of people opposed to it

00:32:46.450 --> 00:32:48.220
in a lot of these tracks.

00:32:48.220 --> 00:32:49.970
I'm just putting this pamphlet up.

00:32:49.970 --> 00:32:51.940
I know you can't read it.

00:32:51.940 --> 00:32:58.800
But you can probably read
what's in the bold type in red.

00:32:58.800 --> 00:33:05.160 position:56%
And that's where you can see this
really sums up most of the arguments

00:33:05.160 --> 00:33:09.610
that were for the status quo.

00:33:09.610 --> 00:33:12.140
And I'll just run through them.

00:33:12.140 --> 00:33:13.840
How are we doing time-wise?

00:33:13.840 --> 00:33:16.530
Okay. I'll run through
them very quickly.

00:33:16.530 --> 00:33:18.350
The mirror of America was one

00:33:18.350 --> 00:33:20.020
that was used throughout
the 20th century.

00:33:20.020 --> 00:33:21.770
And that's basically that northern

00:33:21.770 --> 00:33:24.630
and western Europeans were the
people that settled the country,

00:33:24.630 --> 00:33:28.050
that arguably they made the
country great and it's only fair

00:33:28.050 --> 00:33:30.450
that they get a disproportional
number

00:33:30.450 --> 00:33:32.710
of the visas issued every year.

00:33:32.710 --> 00:33:36.070
This was the status quo
argument of fairness.

00:33:36.070 --> 00:33:39.090
And then the corollary
that it was much easier

00:33:39.090 --> 00:33:42.620
to assimilate these immigrants

00:33:42.620 --> 00:33:45.550
because they were more
like us, so to speak.

00:33:45.550 --> 00:33:51.170
Now anti-communism was a very
important issue in the 1950's.

00:33:51.170 --> 00:33:54.720
But it really waned by the '60's
and didn't come up as much.

00:33:54.720 --> 00:33:57.210
But the issue that really
came up even more was

00:33:57.210 --> 00:33:58.570 position:56%
that looking out for the little guy.

00:33:58.570 --> 00:34:00.160
And you see this in the pamphlet.

00:34:00.160 --> 00:34:02.760
They talk about immigrant
workers that would be competing

00:34:02.760 --> 00:34:06.570
with US workers and
taking jobs away.

00:34:06.570 --> 00:34:08.870
Another argument that
was just emerging

00:34:08.870 --> 00:34:12.420
in the '50's was population
explosion.

00:34:12.420 --> 00:34:15.890
And House immigration subcommittee
had hearings on population

00:34:15.890 --> 00:34:19.320
and immigration, which spent
a lot of time looking at this.

00:34:19.320 --> 00:34:21.800
And this was right about -- for
some of you that might remember,

00:34:21.800 --> 00:34:24.860
this is right about the same
time the book The Population Bomb

00:34:24.860 --> 00:34:26.540
came out.

00:34:26.540 --> 00:34:30.980
And so there was concern
about that issue.

00:34:30.980 --> 00:34:36.930
But at the end of the day, what
I found time and time again

00:34:36.930 --> 00:34:42.090
in the research is that race
was still the driving force.

00:34:42.090 --> 00:34:44.780
And even when you look
at this pamphlet,

00:34:44.780 --> 00:34:50.000
if you look at that last page,
shuffling quotas to admit Asians

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:55.700
and unlimited nonquota orientals
and Negros will be admitted.

00:34:55.700 --> 00:34:59.390
That came up again
and again and again.

00:34:59.390 --> 00:35:01.820
And I'll just do a
couple quick quotes.

00:35:01.820 --> 00:35:04.790
The Daughters of the
American Revolution warned

00:35:04.790 --> 00:35:10.980
against the proliferation of
African immigrants coming.

00:35:10.980 --> 00:35:16.680
Senator Sam Irwin of South Carolina
said the legislation discriminated

00:35:16.680 --> 00:35:18.020
against northern Europeans

00:35:18.020 --> 00:35:20.440
because it treated them
the same as Ethiopians.

00:35:20.440 --> 00:35:24.440 position:56%
"And I don't know of any
contributions that Ethiopia has made

00:35:24.440 --> 00:35:27.420
to America," Senator Irwin said.

00:35:27.420 --> 00:35:30.080
Willis Robertson, who is
Pat Robertson's father,

00:35:30.080 --> 00:35:32.920
was a senator from
Virginia at the time.

00:35:32.920 --> 00:35:36.900
He was the first one that I
found to publicly build the case,

00:35:36.900 --> 00:35:41.220
which I then started finding
everywhere in the primary sources,

00:35:41.220 --> 00:35:45.770
that because -- and this
is a very technical point,

00:35:45.770 --> 00:35:48.770
but it turns out to
be quite important.

00:35:48.770 --> 00:35:51.640
The western hemisphere, as I
told you, had been exempted.

00:35:51.640 --> 00:35:58.140
But not the colonies, if you were
a French of a British colony.

00:35:58.140 --> 00:36:02.400
Well, Jamaica, Trinidad and
Tobago had become independent.

00:36:02.400 --> 00:36:05.590
And this legislation
would have treated them

00:36:05.590 --> 00:36:08.090
like any other western
hemisphere country.

00:36:08.090 --> 00:36:11.170
It would have allowed
them to be unlimited.

00:36:11.170 --> 00:36:15.910
People went ballistic about the
Negroes that would be coming

00:36:15.910 --> 00:36:18.850
in from Jamaica, Trinidad
and Tobago.

00:36:18.850 --> 00:36:23.820
So much so that it became one of
the most compelling arguments used

00:36:23.820 --> 00:36:27.780
to try to put a cap on
the western hemisphere.

00:36:27.780 --> 00:36:34.380
And it's interesting, because --
well, I don't have that much time.

00:36:34.380 --> 00:36:38.430
[Laughs]. Suffice to say, I was
surprised about that finding.

00:36:38.430 --> 00:36:41.140
Then the other issues
that came up --

00:36:41.140 --> 00:36:45.050
and this came out in the
hearings that the house had.

00:36:45.050 --> 00:36:48.750
But it also was becoming much
more commonplace knowledge

00:36:48.750 --> 00:36:50.670
as they led into the final debate.

00:36:50.670 --> 00:36:54.030 position:56%
And that was that the limited quota
immigrants weren't the major portion

00:36:54.030 --> 00:36:56.020
of people coming into the country.

00:36:56.020 --> 00:37:01.470
The western hemisphere was
the largest single category.

00:37:01.470 --> 00:37:04.630
And that nonquota, which I
have depicted in gray here,

00:37:04.630 --> 00:37:07.380
but that's mostly at this point
in time immediate relatives

00:37:07.380 --> 00:37:10.280
of US citizens, was also sizeable.

00:37:10.280 --> 00:37:13.590
So this was leading to the push

00:37:13.590 --> 00:37:17.630
to put all immigration
under a worldwide cap.

00:37:17.630 --> 00:37:21.260
And so when the time came
to be working on this,

00:37:21.260 --> 00:37:25.640
the issue of how many were we going
to let in became quite important.

00:37:25.640 --> 00:37:29.730
And I'm just sharing with you
Congressman Celler's handwritten

00:37:29.730 --> 00:37:32.050
notes as he was calculating, "Well,

00:37:32.050 --> 00:37:34.430
how many people will
my bill let in?"

00:37:34.430 --> 00:37:36.980
And if you look over in the
far corner, I don't expect you

00:37:36.980 --> 00:37:40.700
to be able to read his handwriting
on the monitor, but he was guessing

00:37:40.700 --> 00:37:44.900
that it was about 366,000
that would be coming in.

00:37:44.900 --> 00:37:48.390
The Immigration Naturalization
Service did formal estimates

00:37:48.390 --> 00:37:50.920
and they're depicted
in the yellow bar here.

00:37:50.920 --> 00:37:53.000
And this is based on when
the bill was introduced,

00:37:53.000 --> 00:38:00.820
which was a five-year phase out
of the national origins proposal.

00:38:00.820 --> 00:38:05.710
So you can see they anticipated
an increase in immigration

00:38:05.710 --> 00:38:08.620
and they anticipated
an increase from Asia.

00:38:08.620 --> 00:38:12.750
But they did not, as it turns out,

00:38:12.750 --> 00:38:16.470
anticipate the levels
that we actually had.

00:38:16.470 --> 00:38:19.780
Again, they were using
different legislative language.

00:38:19.780 --> 00:38:22.180
But there are some other things
we can talk about in the Q&amp;A

00:38:22.180 --> 00:38:26.910
if you want to, because I've
taken a pretty long look at this.

00:38:26.910 --> 00:38:30.280
So here are the key features
of what Congress passed.

00:38:30.280 --> 00:38:31.790
They repealed national origins

00:38:31.790 --> 00:38:35.600
and gave a per-country
cap, 20,000 at that time.

00:38:35.600 --> 00:38:37.750
They expanded family-based.

00:38:37.750 --> 00:38:41.900
The employment-based, the push
for high-skilled didn't happen.

00:38:41.900 --> 00:38:44.420
It was set at only 10%.

00:38:44.420 --> 00:38:47.400
So it was a cutback
from current law.

00:38:47.400 --> 00:38:49.410
And the compromise on
the western hemisphere,

00:38:49.410 --> 00:38:53.440
which was a hard-fought
battle ended up --

00:38:53.440 --> 00:38:54.740
they didn't put the
western hemisphere

00:38:54.740 --> 00:38:57.170
under the preference system
at that point in time.

00:38:57.170 --> 00:39:01.130
But they capped it at 120,000.

00:39:01.130 --> 00:39:03.720
The selectivity, I
showed you some pie charts

00:39:03.720 --> 00:39:08.890
of how the McCarran-Walter
Act priorities played out.

00:39:08.890 --> 00:39:12.810
They were a little
better matchup in '65.

00:39:12.810 --> 00:39:17.090
But again, you can see first
preference, US citizens,

00:39:17.090 --> 00:39:20.740
unmarried sons and
daughters were allocated 20%.

00:39:20.740 --> 00:39:23.820
And the first five years used 1%.

00:39:23.820 --> 00:39:26.090
The numbers rolled down.

00:39:26.090 --> 00:39:29.470
And this is the beginning of where
you can see the growth in brothers

00:39:29.470 --> 00:39:32.870
and sisters, which were given --
for the first time they were added

00:39:32.870 --> 00:39:34.170
in the preference category.

00:39:34.170 --> 00:39:38.510
They were given 24% and because of
the roll down they ended up at 28%.

00:39:38.510 --> 00:39:41.610
And over time this
number would grow.

00:39:41.610 --> 00:39:45.150
So this is how the
selectivity was playing out.

00:39:45.150 --> 00:39:50.450
In terms of the western hemisphere
caps, it did have an effect.

00:39:50.450 --> 00:39:52.930
This is just two quick slides.

00:39:52.930 --> 00:39:55.980
You can see that Mexican
migration shifted

00:39:55.980 --> 00:39:59.690
from the western hemisphere
category,

00:39:59.690 --> 00:40:03.010
which was largely employment-based
because you pretty much had

00:40:03.010 --> 00:40:04.500
to have a job to come here.

00:40:04.500 --> 00:40:08.730
To being much more family
oriented and spouses and children

00:40:08.730 --> 00:40:12.050
and other preference categories.

00:40:12.050 --> 00:40:15.020
Similarly, what you see with the
Caribbean and Central America --

00:40:15.020 --> 00:40:18.250
and these numbers at this point
in time are mostly Caribbean.

00:40:18.250 --> 00:40:21.310
You see the Caribbean
was a big winner.

00:40:21.310 --> 00:40:27.880
Their numbers went up substantially
after the '65 act passed.

00:40:27.880 --> 00:40:32.880 position:56%
And they particularly took advantage
of the new preference categories.

00:40:32.880 --> 00:40:35.480
I'm going to drill through
these rather quickly

00:40:35.480 --> 00:40:37.710
but we can come back
to them if you want.

00:40:37.710 --> 00:40:39.850
This is the non-preference
category, which you know

00:40:39.850 --> 00:40:43.670
from the pie charts mopped
up a lot of unused numbers.

00:40:43.670 --> 00:40:48.650
You can see that as that shrunk
the employment-based numbers

00:40:48.650 --> 00:40:50.130
weren't recouped.

00:40:50.130 --> 00:40:56.760
And so employment-based of all
kinds was much smaller post-'65

00:40:56.760 --> 00:40:58.900
than it had been before.

00:40:58.900 --> 00:41:01.900
When you look at professional
and exceptional ability by region

00:41:01.900 --> 00:41:06.290
of the world, again this is not
news, but it points out how Asia

00:41:06.290 --> 00:41:11.260
and opening up Asia, which
had been barred before 1965.

00:41:11.260 --> 00:41:15.280
Asian migrants, Asian
immigrants took full advantage

00:41:15.280 --> 00:41:17.390
of the employment-based
high-skill category.

00:41:17.390 --> 00:41:23.910
And US employers were happy to
recruit and hire Asian workers.

00:41:23.910 --> 00:41:30.170
And in fact, the only thing that
really had those numbers shrink was

00:41:30.170 --> 00:41:34.540
when they put everyone
under the caps,

00:41:34.540 --> 00:41:36.520
when they added the
western hemisphere.

00:41:36.520 --> 00:41:41.060
And when enough of the
family members started coming

00:41:41.060 --> 00:41:44.360
in that they started bumping
against their per-country caps.

00:41:44.360 --> 00:41:47.110
In terms of unskilled
workers and shortage workers,

00:41:47.110 --> 00:41:50.940
the other 10% of the preference
system, it's interesting.

00:41:50.940 --> 00:41:53.970
This kind of plays out like
I think people had intended.

00:41:53.970 --> 00:41:59.800
You can see it's a fairly diverse
flow from all regions of the world

00:41:59.800 --> 00:42:04.610
that were coming in
in this category.

00:42:04.610 --> 00:42:08.490
Family-based is the other big one.

00:42:08.490 --> 00:42:13.500
And when you begin to understand
why did the numbers seem

00:42:13.500 --> 00:42:16.140
to lowball future flows.

00:42:16.140 --> 00:42:19.960
If you look throughout the
'50's, spouses and children

00:42:19.960 --> 00:42:21.780
of US citizens were unlimited then.

00:42:21.780 --> 00:42:24.550
But the numbers were
pretty constant.

00:42:24.550 --> 00:42:28.820
After the '65 act, you see a
growth in immediate relatives.

00:42:28.820 --> 00:42:32.080
And I also pulled out the two
categories that were added

00:42:32.080 --> 00:42:34.870
to immediate relatives
in the 1965 act.

00:42:34.870 --> 00:42:39.300
Most importantly the
parents of US citizens.

00:42:39.300 --> 00:42:43.700
When you look at how the
continuous pattern of spouses

00:42:43.700 --> 00:42:48.070
and children play out, again you
can see Europe stayed pretty much

00:42:48.070 --> 00:42:49.370
the same.

00:42:49.370 --> 00:42:52.420
But you see growth in
Asia and also the shifting

00:42:52.420 --> 00:42:54.590
of the western hemisphere to coming

00:42:54.590 --> 00:42:57.660
in through the family-based
categories.

00:42:57.660 --> 00:43:02.610
Now this one is a key,
because you see parents.

00:43:02.610 --> 00:43:08.200
And I think it's important to
note here that a large portion

00:43:08.200 --> 00:43:11.310
of the growth in parents
of US citizens that came

00:43:11.310 --> 00:43:14.100
after the '65 act were
Asian parents.

00:43:14.100 --> 00:43:16.470 position:56%
Asian families were much more likely

00:43:16.470 --> 00:43:18.980
to bring their parents
to the United States.

00:43:18.980 --> 00:43:22.310
Other parts of the
world followed suit,

00:43:22.310 --> 00:43:25.160
but never in the numbers
that Asian families.

00:43:25.160 --> 00:43:28.950
So this gets into a
fundamental concept.

00:43:28.950 --> 00:43:30.250
So here we are.

00:43:30.250 --> 00:43:31.550
This is the flow today.

00:43:31.550 --> 00:43:32.850
It's much more diverse
than it had been,

00:43:32.850 --> 00:43:35.440
and a lot has been made
about the diversity.

00:43:35.440 --> 00:43:38.120
But I would argue we still
have issues of fairness today.

00:43:38.120 --> 00:43:40.340
They're just not framed
in the context

00:43:40.340 --> 00:43:42.360
of race and national origins.

00:43:42.360 --> 00:43:44.730
They're framed in different ways.

00:43:44.730 --> 00:43:49.050 position:56%
And they're tough choices, just like
they were in the '50's and '60's,

00:43:49.050 --> 00:43:53.520
to decide what is the proper
balance that we should have

00:43:53.520 --> 00:43:55.160
in our immigration policy.

00:43:55.160 --> 00:43:56.950
Who should we select?

00:43:56.950 --> 00:44:00.320
How will that affect
apportionment and politics?

00:44:00.320 --> 00:44:04.280
And so I am going to conclude
my remarks and turn it

00:44:04.280 --> 00:44:09.850
over to Susan Martin and Marat
Tienda to offer some commentary.

