Okay. Thank you.

00:44:37.760 --> 00:44:39.890
Thank you so much to the
Kluge Center for hosting Ruth,

00:44:39.890 --> 00:44:42.870
because this is a phenomenal
project.

00:44:42.870 --> 00:44:47.320
And when Ruth told me that she
was applying for this fellowship

00:44:47.320 --> 00:44:51.300
and wanted to work on the
1965 act, I was very excited

00:44:51.300 --> 00:44:55.930
because there really hasn't been
the type of analysis of the act

00:44:55.930 --> 00:44:58.850
that she has been able to do.

00:44:58.850 --> 00:45:03.010
And seeing the results now,
I'm absolutely delighted

00:45:03.010 --> 00:45:07.440
that she spent the
last year doing this.

00:45:07.440 --> 00:45:10.820
And great use of cartoons too.

00:45:10.820 --> 00:45:13.120
That was one thing
Ruth mentioned to me

00:45:13.120 --> 00:45:15.600
when she was developing
the proposal,

00:45:15.600 --> 00:45:20.350
that she had cartoons
and wanted to use them.

00:45:20.350 --> 00:45:25.400
But hearing the way in which she
was able to tease out the thoughts

00:45:25.400 --> 00:45:32.060
of the time and the concerns from
those graphics is just fantastic.

00:45:32.060 --> 00:45:35.300
I really want to congratulate
you on this.

00:45:35.300 --> 00:45:37.860
I agree with most of the
assessment, or just about all

00:45:37.860 --> 00:45:40.680
of the assessment of
the core issues.

00:45:40.680 --> 00:45:45.350
I think the three areas are
perfect ones in terms of the role

00:45:45.350 --> 00:45:47.900
of prejudice and xenophobia.

00:45:47.900 --> 00:45:52.420 position:56%
It's not that everyone who's opposed
to immigration is xenophobic.

00:45:52.420 --> 00:45:57.370
And I think that's an
important point to carry away.

00:45:57.370 --> 00:45:59.840
There are a lot of good
reasons for being concerned

00:45:59.840 --> 00:46:01.340
about that aspect of immigration.

00:46:01.340 --> 00:46:05.480
The problem is that the
emotions that are carried

00:46:05.480 --> 00:46:10.420
because of this fear of the other
is what makes it so difficult

00:46:10.420 --> 00:46:15.220
to have a rational discussion
about those very concerns.

00:46:15.220 --> 00:46:21.020 position:56%
And as a result, it becomes a binary
action of you're for or against.

00:46:21.020 --> 00:46:24.500
Not one where you can actually
talk about what are the strengths

00:46:24.500 --> 00:46:26.870
and weaknesses and
what are good policies.

00:46:26.870 --> 00:46:32.430
And I think we saw that very much
in that period leading up to 1924

00:46:32.430 --> 00:46:38.900
and then continuing
through until 1965.

00:46:38.900 --> 00:46:43.930
Selectivity is a major issue
in today's debate as well

00:46:43.930 --> 00:46:46.140
as it has been historically.

00:46:46.140 --> 00:46:51.270
Prior to the Nash Largins
quote is the US mostly tried

00:46:51.270 --> 00:46:59.250
to regulate immigration from
the 1870's to '24 by determining

00:46:59.250 --> 00:47:01.470
who had the qualities
we wanted to admit.

00:47:01.470 --> 00:47:06.460
And it was issues that I think
everyone could agree with:

00:47:06.460 --> 00:47:09.510
not to admit people
with criminal records,

00:47:09.510 --> 00:47:12.670
certain contagious
diseases, things of that sort.

00:47:12.670 --> 00:47:15.920
But then it got to
very, very shaky grounds

00:47:15.920 --> 00:47:19.210 position:56%
like who is of good moral character.

00:47:19.210 --> 00:47:21.230
That's very, very subjective.

00:47:21.230 --> 00:47:24.690
And I remember also
there were crimes

00:47:24.690 --> 00:47:28.250
of moral turpitude
and what that means.

00:47:28.250 --> 00:47:35.200
And there's a famous case in which
there was a British aristocratic

00:47:35.200 --> 00:47:40.910
couple who had a divorce and
each had accuse the other

00:47:40.910 --> 00:47:43.960
of adultery as the basis for it.

00:47:43.960 --> 00:47:46.250
They were coming to the
US on different boats

00:47:46.250 --> 00:47:49.240
at almost precisely the same time.

00:47:49.240 --> 00:47:51.680
He was admitted and she was barred

00:47:51.680 --> 00:47:54.470
because she committed a
crime of moral turpitude.

00:47:54.470 --> 00:48:00.510
So you've got very interesting
ways in which the policies play

00:48:00.510 --> 00:48:03.730
out when you're talking
about selectivity.

00:48:03.730 --> 00:48:06.180
And then the importance of power

00:48:06.180 --> 00:48:08.880
and apportionment is
absolutely right on,

00:48:08.880 --> 00:48:12.250
as we can see today in the debate.

00:48:12.250 --> 00:48:17.390
But I must say quickly in my time
also, what I see as the lessons

00:48:17.390 --> 00:48:21.370 position:56%
of the 1965 act and what preceded it

00:48:21.370 --> 00:48:25.590
for today's debate on
immigration reform.

00:48:25.590 --> 00:48:29.980
The first key issue I think is
that it takes an awfully long time

00:48:29.980 --> 00:48:32.570
to get immigration reform.

00:48:32.570 --> 00:48:38.580
And it's been since 1990 that
there's been the last major reform

00:48:38.580 --> 00:48:40.830
in legal admissions to the US.

00:48:40.830 --> 00:48:45.290
1986 was the major
reforms for dealing

00:48:45.290 --> 00:48:49.570
with unauthorized illegal
immigration into the country.

00:48:49.570 --> 00:48:53.690
And the last series
of serious debate

00:48:53.690 --> 00:48:56.980
on immigration started
about 10 years ago.

00:48:56.980 --> 00:49:00.510
So we've had 25 years
since the last reforms.

00:49:00.510 --> 00:49:05.280
We've had 10 years of bills
being introduced, debated,

00:49:05.280 --> 00:49:11.300
passing sometimes one
house, never both on that.

00:49:11.300 --> 00:49:16.560
But as we've heard from Ruth,
the same thing exactly happened,

00:49:16.560 --> 00:49:20.430
both in terms of getting
to the '24 legislation.

00:49:20.430 --> 00:49:23.380
It took 50 years or
so of debate to decide

00:49:23.380 --> 00:49:25.880
on the national origins quotas.

00:49:25.880 --> 00:49:31.930
And then from '24 to '65
before we could get the change

00:49:31.930 --> 00:49:34.340
in those policies.

00:49:34.340 --> 00:49:37.640
Although there were incremental
changes in the interim.

00:49:37.640 --> 00:49:42.620
But the fundamental changes
really take a long, long time.

00:49:42.620 --> 00:49:46.470
And so we shouldn't be surprised
that we're having difficulty today.

00:49:46.470 --> 00:49:52.120
That's part of our -- almost the
DNA of immigration in this country.

00:49:52.120 --> 00:49:56.670 position:56%
Part of the reason for that is we
are so ambivalent about immigration.

00:49:56.670 --> 00:50:01.310
I think if most people realized
that what they are saying today

00:50:01.310 --> 00:50:05.220
about immigrants is exactly
what was said against them

00:50:05.220 --> 00:50:09.720
when their forefathers came,
they'd be absolutely shocked.

00:50:09.720 --> 00:50:13.850
They don't see that connection,
although it is so strong.

00:50:13.850 --> 00:50:17.380
We always look with rose-colored
glasses at our forebears

00:50:17.380 --> 00:50:21.620
and deep suspicion about the
people who are coming in today.

00:50:21.620 --> 00:50:24.410
And so that's a problem.

00:50:24.410 --> 00:50:27.390
The second problem is there
have always been bedfellows

00:50:27.390 --> 00:50:28.690
on the immigration issue.

00:50:28.690 --> 00:50:32.580
As that chart showed,
you can't predict

00:50:32.580 --> 00:50:35.970
in very easy ways who's
going to be in favor

00:50:35.970 --> 00:50:38.610
and who's going to be opposed.

00:50:38.610 --> 00:50:41.350
And one of the divisions that
I've written a lot about --

00:50:41.350 --> 00:50:45.350
and Ruth mentioned some
of the work I've done --

00:50:45.350 --> 00:50:48.530
is that there are always
divisions between what people think

00:50:48.530 --> 00:50:52.950
about immigration -- meaning how
many people should be admitted --

00:50:52.950 --> 00:50:55.860
and what do they think about
immigrants, meaning what kind

00:50:55.860 --> 00:50:57.900
of right people should have.

00:50:57.900 --> 00:51:03.230
And these coalitions
change depending on which

00:51:03.230 --> 00:51:05.900
of those issues you're
really talking about.

00:51:05.900 --> 00:51:10.800
And the selectivity issue
gets into play on both levels

00:51:10.800 --> 00:51:13.580
of immigration and of immigrants.

00:51:13.580 --> 00:51:15.850
And we're still seeing
strange bedfellows.

00:51:15.850 --> 00:51:19.650
Although I think today we're
seeing more partisan politics

00:51:19.650 --> 00:51:23.170
on immigration than at
least historically was true.

00:51:23.170 --> 00:51:28.880
And I've been working on public
policy issues on immigration

00:51:28.880 --> 00:51:34.610
since 1979 and it's more
partisan than I have ever seen it.

00:51:34.610 --> 00:51:36.730
And that makes it very,
very difficult

00:51:36.730 --> 00:51:38.920
to get to where we want to hit.

00:51:38.920 --> 00:51:45.890
And that means another point that
came out of Ruth's talk is the need

00:51:45.890 --> 00:51:47.190
for political leadership.

00:51:47.190 --> 00:51:51.570
It's those political figures
particularly presidents

00:51:51.570 --> 00:51:53.670
that really have to lead the way.

00:51:53.670 --> 00:51:58.730
But what's difficult about that
in the context of immigration is

00:51:58.730 --> 00:52:03.610
that immigration is a congressional
prerogative and is seen as being

00:52:03.610 --> 00:52:05.710
in the purview of Congress.

00:52:05.710 --> 00:52:09.600
And presidents generally,
executive branches have not had

00:52:09.600 --> 00:52:10.900
much influence.

00:52:10.900 --> 00:52:13.290
So trying to pull that influence

00:52:13.290 --> 00:52:16.680
into the debate can
be very difficult.

00:52:16.680 --> 00:52:19.820
And so you also need strong
congressional leadership

00:52:19.820 --> 00:52:24.850
which is willing to take on a
lot of interest to get there.

00:52:24.850 --> 00:52:31.060
Final point that came out
of Ruth's presentation is

00:52:31.060 --> 00:52:33.480
that there are always
unintended consequences

00:52:33.480 --> 00:52:37.850
of whatever legislation
is developed.

00:52:37.850 --> 00:52:40.610 position:56%
She mentioned that there was a shift

00:52:40.610 --> 00:52:43.880
from national origins
to per-country quotas.

00:52:43.880 --> 00:52:48.080
And those per-country quotas after
a certain period of time then led

00:52:48.080 --> 00:52:51.130
to huge backlogs and problems

00:52:51.130 --> 00:52:54.590
in having an efficient
system for immigration.

00:52:54.590 --> 00:53:02.100 position:56%
One of the solutions to that, the
one that has not been a part of much

00:53:02.100 --> 00:53:06.410
of the legislative debate is
having more flexible policies

00:53:06.410 --> 00:53:10.360
that can be changed
as conditions change,

00:53:10.360 --> 00:53:17.870 position:56%
as we have new economic conditions,
new technology, new everything else.

00:53:17.870 --> 00:53:21.410
Instead we have this
written in concrete

00:53:21.410 --> 00:53:24.170
and not change for
decades and decades.

00:53:24.170 --> 00:53:30.610
The signs I don't think are very
promising today for having any kind

00:53:30.610 --> 00:53:34.330
of comprehensive immigration
reform in the near future.

00:53:34.330 --> 00:53:37.850
Perhaps after the next election,
depending on where it goes.

00:53:37.850 --> 00:53:42.550
But depending on where it goes it
could be super good or to the bad,

00:53:42.550 --> 00:53:47.010
depending on where you're sitting
as to what actually happens.

00:53:47.010 --> 00:53:50.960
I think incremental changes,
as was true in the '50's

00:53:50.960 --> 00:53:53.600
and other periods, are more likely.

00:53:53.600 --> 00:53:57.130
But they have to be
carefully tailored

00:53:57.130 --> 00:53:59.840
to make the system more effective

00:53:59.840 --> 00:54:04.550
but not become the barrier
themselves to further reform.

00:54:04.550 --> 00:54:08.670
That's the more fundamental nature.

00:54:08.670 --> 00:54:11.970
But you know, it did
take 40 years to get rid

00:54:11.970 --> 00:54:13.990
of the national origins quotas.

00:54:13.990 --> 00:54:19.180
I'm an optimist by nature and
I really hope that the kind

00:54:19.180 --> 00:54:24.540
of information that is coming
out of Ruth's project can be used

00:54:24.540 --> 00:54:30.560
by policy makers as well as
advocates to press for the type

00:54:30.560 --> 00:54:33.160
of immigration reform
that we need now.

00:54:33.160 --> 00:54:37.820
Which ultimately is going to have
to be as fundamental as the reform

00:54:37.820 --> 00:54:40.770
in 1965 that she's describing.

