00:55:59.200 --> 00:56:01.900
of this legislation could
anticipate the future

00:56:01.900 --> 00:56:06.000
in which these consequences are
playing out, intended or not.

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:10.160
And so there are many critics of
the broken immigration system,

00:56:10.160 --> 00:56:13.450
and they point out these
unintended consequences

00:56:13.450 --> 00:56:15.150
to pick up where you left off.

00:56:15.150 --> 00:56:16.660
And I was a piece of that.

00:56:16.660 --> 00:56:20.590
It was not going to
change the racial mix.

00:56:20.590 --> 00:56:22.070
Well, it sure did.

00:56:22.070 --> 00:56:25.130
It won't displace US
workers, and we made sure

00:56:25.130 --> 00:56:27.390
by restricting the unskilled visas.

00:56:27.390 --> 00:56:28.980
Except that there's a back door

00:56:28.980 --> 00:56:32.070
and human ingenuity
always trumps legislation.

00:56:32.070 --> 00:56:34.000
It won't raise the level.

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:37.800
Well, yes, if you think
it's a linear process.

00:56:37.800 --> 00:56:40.200
But by design, by design,

00:56:40.200 --> 00:56:45.460
the legislation was actually
designed to have a multiplier.

00:56:45.460 --> 00:56:47.650 position:56%
Immigration is not a linear process.

00:56:47.650 --> 00:56:50.810
You could set the ceilings,
but when you're allowing --

00:56:50.810 --> 00:56:55.090
or you change it with family
reunification, families don't come

00:56:55.090 --> 00:56:57.260
in packages of one or two.

00:56:57.260 --> 00:56:58.950
They come in multiple packages.

00:56:58.950 --> 00:57:02.960 position:56%
So one could argue that in many ways
the legislation did exactly what it

00:57:02.960 --> 00:57:04.430
was supposed to do.

00:57:04.430 --> 00:57:08.380
We made family reunification,
put our values on the table.

00:57:08.380 --> 00:57:09.680
Civil Rights.

00:57:09.680 --> 00:57:11.100
You cast this in the
context of the Civil Rights.

00:57:11.100 --> 00:57:13.010
We were hoping not to be racist.

00:57:13.010 --> 00:57:15.190
So that context turns out
to be really important

00:57:15.190 --> 00:57:17.940
about what was acceptable
at the time.

00:57:17.940 --> 00:57:21.580
So family reunification
is actually working.

00:57:21.580 --> 00:57:25.170
Two-thirds of our admissions
are family-based immigrants,

00:57:25.170 --> 00:57:27.280
whether they're within
cap or out of cap.

00:57:27.280 --> 00:57:31.340
That's just the opposite of what
happened in Australia or Canada.

00:57:31.340 --> 00:57:34.470
They deliberately made sure
when it was going toward family,

00:57:34.470 --> 00:57:36.780
they deliberately changed
their policies

00:57:36.780 --> 00:57:40.670
so that they would have had
the skill mix and be two-thirds

00:57:40.670 --> 00:57:42.470
and the other be one-third.

00:57:42.470 --> 00:57:44.170
Because they were going
in the same direction.

00:57:44.170 --> 00:57:47.230
So they took legislative acts
and we can learn from them,

00:57:47.230 --> 00:57:48.530
because they learned from us.

00:57:48.530 --> 00:57:49.830
And they said, "Oh, we
don't want to do this.

00:57:49.830 --> 00:57:51.130
We're going to fix it."

00:57:51.130 --> 00:57:52.430
And they did.

00:57:52.430 --> 00:57:53.730
They didn't fight.

00:57:53.730 --> 00:57:55.030 position:56%
I mean, it wasn't easy there either.

00:57:55.030 --> 00:57:58.430
But I just published a paper
-- well it just got accepted.

00:57:58.430 --> 00:58:00.740
I've done a couple of
them that focus a bit

00:58:00.740 --> 00:58:02.160
on the unintended consequences.

00:58:02.160 --> 00:58:03.860
One that's just going

00:58:03.860 --> 00:58:06.070
to be forthcoming is called
Multiplying Diversity.

00:58:06.070 --> 00:58:09.810
And what I've done is actually
compute the immigration multipliers

00:58:09.810 --> 00:58:13.040
by the family categories
to show why it is

00:58:13.040 --> 00:58:16.470
that the Asians surpassed
the Latin Americans.

00:58:16.470 --> 00:58:18.260
Not recently, as many people write,

00:58:18.260 --> 00:58:22.250
but actually much before
the Immigration Reform

00:58:22.250 --> 00:58:24.990
and Control Act allowed
the legalization program.

00:58:24.990 --> 00:58:29.080
But the Asian multiplier
took off big time.

00:58:29.080 --> 00:58:30.760
But it was by design.

00:58:30.760 --> 00:58:32.170
You could argue that
it was by design.

00:58:32.170 --> 00:58:33.470
They didn't expect it.

00:58:33.470 --> 00:58:38.400
They were thinking linear,
but they crafted multiplier.

00:58:38.400 --> 00:58:42.480
So they did not anticipate how many
people were going to naturalize.

00:58:42.480 --> 00:58:47.070
If you made citizenship a
requirement to sponsor relatives,

00:58:47.070 --> 00:58:48.730
well how do you become a citizen?

00:58:48.730 --> 00:58:50.310
You naturalize.

00:58:50.310 --> 00:58:52.720
Bring in immigrants, let them
naturalize and then they bring

00:58:52.720 --> 00:58:54.170
in their relatives, right?

00:58:54.170 --> 00:58:56.140
So you could put caps
on certain categories.

00:58:56.140 --> 00:58:59.230
We did. But that didn't stop
the uncapped categories.

00:58:59.230 --> 00:59:02.610 position:56%
And those uncapped categories turned
out to be a really important driver,

00:59:02.610 --> 00:59:04.800
but also the family caps.

00:59:04.800 --> 00:59:08.630
So this expansion, I've
written about the expansion

00:59:08.630 --> 00:59:10.900
of the definition of
immediate family relatives

00:59:10.900 --> 00:59:14.100
that you highlighted in your
presentation to include parents.

00:59:14.100 --> 00:59:16.740
I mean, who's against grandparents?

00:59:16.740 --> 00:59:18.960
You want to bring them in to
take care of your children.

00:59:18.960 --> 00:59:21.610
That's what they told me
when I was presenting some

00:59:21.610 --> 00:59:24.330
of these materials early
on at the PA meeting.

00:59:24.330 --> 00:59:27.230
And I said, "You know, one of
the unintended consequences --

00:59:27.230 --> 00:59:29.040
we wanted to reunite family.

00:59:29.040 --> 00:59:30.340
That was a design.

00:59:30.340 --> 00:59:32.720
But the default has
been that we have a rise

00:59:32.720 --> 00:59:35.080
in late-age immigration."

00:59:35.080 --> 00:59:37.800
We want immigrants to
be in the labor force,

00:59:37.800 --> 00:59:41.840
but the share that are ages 50
and over has increased from 11%

00:59:41.840 --> 00:59:46.320
in 1980 to I think it's 17% now.

00:59:46.320 --> 00:59:47.620
That's a big change.

00:59:47.620 --> 00:59:50.370
You say, "Well, 17%
ages 50 and over.

00:59:50.370 --> 00:59:53.240
At 50 you still have a
lot of working life."

00:59:53.240 --> 00:59:54.740
Maybe. You have to learn English.

00:59:54.740 --> 00:59:56.470
You have to see if
you can be certified.

00:59:56.470 --> 00:59:58.650
You have to see if you can earn
your social security credits.

00:59:58.650 --> 00:59:59.950
We move on.

00:59:59.950 --> 01:00:01.640
So this is an issue.

01:00:01.640 --> 01:00:04.530
This linear extrapolation
was an oversight.

01:00:04.530 --> 01:00:06.270
I don't think that
they had anticipated,

01:00:06.270 --> 01:00:08.230
and you mentioned that
in your address.

01:00:08.230 --> 01:00:09.530
So how does it matter?

01:00:09.530 --> 01:00:13.420
Well, Congress did legislate
this, but recall 1965 --

01:00:13.420 --> 01:00:16.090
what else was going on
besides the Civil Rights Act?

01:00:16.090 --> 01:00:18.110
We were in a great mood.

01:00:18.110 --> 01:00:20.060
We were reeling from the baby boom.

01:00:20.060 --> 01:00:21.460
That would be moi.

01:00:21.460 --> 01:00:26.530
So the Congress was really from the
baby boom, and schools and states

01:00:26.530 --> 01:00:30.490
and localities were all fussing
about these classrooms of 36.

01:00:30.490 --> 01:00:33.650
We weren't worried
about population aging.

01:00:33.650 --> 01:00:39.040
So we modified Social Security Act
to create Medicare and Medicaid.

01:00:39.040 --> 01:00:42.930
Today, 50 years later we're not
saying, "Ooh, wait a minute.

01:00:42.930 --> 01:00:45.060
We've got to think
this through again."

01:00:45.060 --> 01:00:49.490
So at the time, at the time it made
sense, but it was done in a way

01:00:49.490 --> 01:00:51.070
that has not been modified.

01:00:51.070 --> 01:00:53.000
And these unintended consequences

01:00:53.000 --> 01:00:56.160
which were not intended
continue to play out.

01:00:56.160 --> 01:00:57.740
So times have changed.

01:00:57.740 --> 01:00:59.420
The world has changed.

01:00:59.420 --> 01:01:02.380
The desired sending
countries, they didn't pan

01:01:02.380 --> 01:01:05.080 position:56%
out from the very beginning because
of the Martial Act and other changes

01:01:05.080 --> 01:01:07.890
that were taking place in
Europe in the postwar period.

01:01:07.890 --> 01:01:10.170
They've aged even faster
than the United States.

01:01:10.170 --> 01:01:13.950
So they're not going to be
coming here any time soon.

01:01:13.950 --> 01:01:16.490
We have aged as a nation
less quickly

01:01:16.490 --> 01:01:20.870
than our other OECD competitors,
thanks to immigration,

01:01:20.870 --> 01:01:23.820
because the immigrants
are having children

01:01:23.820 --> 01:01:25.350
and they had higher fertility.

01:01:25.350 --> 01:01:27.340
So that's kept us a little younger.

01:01:27.340 --> 01:01:29.540
It's intensified our
diversification.

01:01:29.540 --> 01:01:32.350
So if we're all over
the diversity issue,

01:01:32.350 --> 01:01:35.080
well that's a program
that's already in process.

01:01:35.080 --> 01:01:38.960
And that's not going to
change any time soon.

01:01:38.960 --> 01:01:42.450
So there's a glaring age
divide also in the world

01:01:42.450 --> 01:01:46.630
with the southern nations are very
young and they're growing rapidly.

01:01:46.630 --> 01:01:49.280
Some of them have still
very high fertility.

01:01:49.280 --> 01:01:52.570
The north is aging quite rapidly.

01:01:52.570 --> 01:01:54.720
So these are the facts.

01:01:54.720 --> 01:01:56.430
So future immigration
is not going to come

01:01:56.430 --> 01:01:57.850
from our former sending countries

01:01:57.850 --> 01:02:00.070
and it never did really
when we expected.

01:02:00.070 --> 01:02:03.300
Spain, Italy and Germany, they're
now countries of immigration

01:02:03.300 --> 01:02:06.280
and they've had this really
rapid turnaround from sending

01:02:06.280 --> 01:02:10.220
to being receivers of immigration.

01:02:10.220 --> 01:02:13.090
So if we're going to have
immigration, let's face it,

01:02:13.090 --> 01:02:16.490
it's going to come mainly from
Asia and Africa, Latin America.

01:02:16.490 --> 01:02:19.550
But Latin American
fertility has slowed.

01:02:19.550 --> 01:02:22.350
Mexican immigration
today is net zero.

01:02:22.350 --> 01:02:23.740
It has been for several years.

01:02:23.740 --> 01:02:26.050
And a lot of people find
that really hard to believe

01:02:26.050 --> 01:02:28.570
because they're looking
in the rearview mirror.

01:02:28.570 --> 01:02:31.550
We should tell our politicians
when they open their mouths

01:02:31.550 --> 01:02:36.150
to look forward and not in
yesterday's projections.

01:02:36.150 --> 01:02:38.520
So demography is not destiny.

01:02:38.520 --> 01:02:40.540
That is certainly not
the position I take.

01:02:40.540 --> 01:02:41.840
But it's highly relevant

01:02:41.840 --> 01:02:44.730
for understanding the future
contours of our immigration.

01:02:44.730 --> 01:02:47.430
And the question is, will
those contours result

01:02:47.430 --> 01:02:51.140
from deliberate rational
policy decision making?

01:02:51.140 --> 01:02:54.380
Which Susan and I haven't
lost hope for and I won't,

01:02:54.380 --> 01:02:55.720
as long as I'm still writing.

01:02:55.720 --> 01:02:59.730
Or the default of a failure to act?

01:02:59.730 --> 01:03:01.670
The default of a failure to act.

01:03:01.670 --> 01:03:04.130
Not to decide is to decide.

01:03:04.130 --> 01:03:08.190
So what I asked my students when
I teach as a policy exercise,

01:03:08.190 --> 01:03:13.470
I love this Legomsky paper
called Immigration from Scratch.

01:03:13.470 --> 01:03:17.350 position:56%
And I tell them from the outset that
all sovereign nations have the right

01:03:17.350 --> 01:03:22.850
to decide who to admit, how many,
when and under what auspices.

01:03:22.850 --> 01:03:25.380
The balance of family,
humanitarian and skills.

01:03:25.380 --> 01:03:27.130
Every nation has that as sovereign.

01:03:27.130 --> 01:03:29.790
That's what national
boundaries are for.

01:03:29.790 --> 01:03:32.940
So they exist and that's
why we have immigration.

01:03:32.940 --> 01:03:37.270
That said, abiding by international
conventions for refugees,

01:03:37.270 --> 01:03:39.320
which is always still
a dicey challenge.

01:03:39.320 --> 01:03:44.430
So that said, given
your lens of fairness,

01:03:44.430 --> 01:03:47.730
how will fairness then
play out in the future?

01:03:47.730 --> 01:03:52.620
If 50 years from now
we wanted to project

01:03:52.620 --> 01:03:57.740
and have your protg looking back
and doing the same Kluge lecture,

01:03:57.740 --> 01:04:02.650 position:56%
what would they say 50 years from
now about fairness and our adherence

01:04:02.650 --> 01:04:07.550
to our democratic ideals through
immigration, through inclusion.

01:04:07.550 --> 01:04:12.260
We can either harness and
manage immigration by design,

01:04:12.260 --> 01:04:15.010
as we have tried to do, and
it's a very difficult one

01:04:15.010 --> 01:04:17.100
when you're dealing
with human ingenuity

01:04:17.100 --> 01:04:20.600
and moral and ideological issues.

01:04:20.600 --> 01:04:25.380
Broadening the front door,
strategically, deliberately.

01:04:25.380 --> 01:04:27.170 position:56%
Acknowledging the current realities.

01:04:27.170 --> 01:04:30.930
Or are we going to manage it by
default and allowing the back door

01:04:30.930 --> 01:04:33.900
to swing back and forth and going
in a circle the way we're doing?

01:04:33.900 --> 01:04:36.100
That's to do nothing, to be frozen.

01:04:36.100 --> 01:04:38.350
And not to decide is to decide.

01:04:38.350 --> 01:04:43.470
So proactive versus incremental
reactive, which is what we've done

01:04:43.470 --> 01:04:46.800
with little legislation and raising
the ceiling on temporary workers

01:04:46.800 --> 01:04:48.620
and raising the caps here and there

01:04:48.620 --> 01:04:51.680
without doing the fundamental
questioning of what is it

01:04:51.680 --> 01:04:54.500
that we're expecting from
our immigration policy?

01:04:54.500 --> 01:04:57.650
And I will go with one
final thought about the need

01:04:57.650 --> 01:05:00.810 position:56%
to also consider integration policy.

01:05:00.810 --> 01:05:04.080
I am on the National
Academy Panel on Fiscal

01:05:04.080 --> 01:05:06.370 position:56%
and Economic Impacts of Immigration.

01:05:06.370 --> 01:05:09.270
But the twin panel is on
immigrant integration.

01:05:09.270 --> 01:05:12.000
It shows that immigrants
are integrating,

01:05:12.000 --> 01:05:13.670
but we could do a much better job

01:05:13.670 --> 01:05:17.990
and really harness the immigration
dividend going forward instead

01:05:17.990 --> 01:05:19.400
of having the default option

01:05:19.400 --> 01:05:23.960
and sub-optimally let immigrants
contribute to this great nation.

01:05:23.960 --> 01:05:26.510
Thank you.

