who had both been very active
in the movement of Latinos

01:17:24.050 --> 01:17:26.220
in the labor movement and kind

01:17:26.220 --> 01:17:29.720
of the growing Latino
Civil Rights movement.

01:17:29.720 --> 01:17:34.360
They wanted the shift away
from Bracero to a legal flow.

01:17:34.360 --> 01:17:38.220
They did not want to
come in as temporary,

01:17:38.220 --> 01:17:39.930
do the job and be sent back.

01:17:39.930 --> 01:17:42.900
They wanted it to be a
permanent flow on a track

01:17:42.900 --> 01:17:46.500
like every other LPR, to be a
citizen if they chose to be.

01:17:46.500 --> 01:17:51.860
And that was why I notice -- one
of the reasons I noticed a shift.

01:17:51.860 --> 01:17:53.720
Because the western
hemisphere exemption

01:17:53.720 --> 01:17:56.240
in the 1920's was supported
by the south.

01:17:56.240 --> 01:17:59.880
And the south supported Bracero.

01:17:59.880 --> 01:18:05.870 position:56%
By the time we got to '65, it wasn't
-- and even in the '50's, Phil Hart

01:18:05.870 --> 01:18:07.510
and Emanuel Celler who I think

01:18:07.510 --> 01:18:10.100
by anyone's standards would
be considered liberal,

01:18:10.100 --> 01:18:14.200
they had put the western hemisphere
under the worldwide ceiling.

01:18:14.200 --> 01:18:18.340
There was a flip, and I'm
still trying to understand it.

01:18:18.340 --> 01:18:24.170
But part of it was, "Let's end
the temporary exploitative flows.

01:18:24.170 --> 01:18:26.780
Let's create a permanent flow."

01:18:26.780 --> 01:18:30.100
And also in terms of why
the south pulled away,

01:18:30.100 --> 01:18:32.660
I think it was the mechanization
of cotton and sugar cane

01:18:32.660 --> 01:18:35.990
that dramatically affected
the desire of the south

01:18:35.990 --> 01:18:41.420 position:56%
to have unlimited workers coming in.

01:18:41.420 --> 01:18:42.770
So it was largely the --

01:18:42.770 --> 01:18:45.310
&gt;&gt; Susan Martin: It was
much slower in Texas.

01:18:45.310 --> 01:18:46.930
They had the citrus industry.

01:18:46.930 --> 01:18:48.230
&gt;&gt; Ruth Wasem: Yes, yes.

01:18:48.230 --> 01:18:49.530
&gt;&gt; Susan Martin: They
had cotton still.

01:18:49.530 --> 01:18:50.830
I mean, I'm from Texas, y'all.

01:18:50.830 --> 01:18:54.770
So it took a longer period of time
for that type of mechanization.

01:18:54.770 --> 01:18:57.130
But remember the Bracero
program had two pieces.

01:18:57.130 --> 01:18:59.260
The first part, Texas
was not allowed

01:18:59.260 --> 01:19:00.650
to participate in the first half.

01:19:00.650 --> 01:19:04.600
1945-48, that was World
War II, labor shortages.

01:19:04.600 --> 01:19:08.040
And then they had a hiatus, but
they continued it informally.

01:19:08.040 --> 01:19:14.290
And the demand, the taste for
having this cheap, pliable,

01:19:14.290 --> 01:19:17.640
no-regulation labor force
got to be really good.

01:19:17.640 --> 01:19:20.900
The appetite for that kind of
labor force became really high

01:19:20.900 --> 01:19:22.200
in California and Texas.

01:19:22.200 --> 01:19:25.110 position:56%
So everybody was doing it like we do
today with unauthorized immigration.

01:19:25.110 --> 01:19:26.520
We turn a blind eye.

01:19:26.520 --> 01:19:27.880
And so that was going
on for a long time.

01:19:27.880 --> 01:19:32.390
For the second, for the renewal,
the impetus for the public life

01:19:32.390 --> 01:19:35.190
in '78 was for the Korean conflict.

01:19:35.190 --> 01:19:39.330
In between those two
formal bills was the peak

01:19:39.330 --> 01:19:42.590
of Braceros coming to the US.

01:19:42.590 --> 01:19:45.160
It had temporarily ended.

01:19:45.160 --> 01:19:48.200
Texas was allowed to
participate the second round

01:19:48.200 --> 01:19:50.620
because they had the
Texas Proviso, right?

01:19:50.620 --> 01:19:55.110
And that's where we wrote into our
legislation that it was a felony

01:19:55.110 --> 01:19:58.300
to be in a country,
but it was not a --

01:19:58.300 --> 01:20:01.270
it was a felony to
transport to harbor,

01:20:01.270 --> 01:20:05.020
to do everything except
purposes of employment.

01:20:05.020 --> 01:20:08.750
So we had la viva la contratoin
in our legislation written

01:20:08.750 --> 01:20:11.590
that made it okay for employers

01:20:11.590 --> 01:20:16.420
to hire unauthorized immigrants
alongside the Bracero program

01:20:16.420 --> 01:20:18.530
which made the exploitation
of the Bracero program --

01:20:18.530 --> 01:20:20.830
there were several incidents
in California that led to this.

01:20:20.830 --> 01:20:23.220
They said, "We've had enough."

01:20:23.220 --> 01:20:27.900
So we had these two, the formal
and informal guest worker program.

01:20:27.900 --> 01:20:29.520 position:56%
Which is kind of what we have today,

01:20:29.520 --> 01:20:32.990
except that the fertility
in Mexico has declined.

01:20:32.990 --> 01:20:36.490
The demand for the supply of
extra workers has been shrinking.

01:20:36.490 --> 01:20:39.280
So this is a window of
opportunity starting to close.

01:20:39.280 --> 01:20:41.170
And we haven't figured
out how we want

01:20:41.170 --> 01:20:43.460
to handle low-skill
workers in our country.

01:20:43.460 --> 01:20:45.320
Which is really the bottom line.

01:20:45.320 --> 01:20:50.240 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Ruth Wasem: And to follow up your
point, I did a role call analysis

01:20:50.240 --> 01:20:53.170
of support for the Bracero program,
which was the same Congress --

01:20:53.170 --> 01:20:54.860
the legislation you were referring

01:20:54.860 --> 01:20:58.550
to that passed the '52
act, and it was identical.

01:20:58.550 --> 01:21:01.880
The people that supported
Bracero also supported national

01:21:01.880 --> 01:21:03.180
origin quotas.

01:21:03.180 --> 01:21:06.500
It was temporary.

01:21:06.500 --> 01:21:07.800
Yeah?

01:21:07.800 --> 01:21:11.240
&gt;&gt; I think he has a question.

01:21:11.240 --> 01:21:14.590
&gt;&gt; Ruth Wasem: One more question.

01:21:14.590 --> 01:21:15.890
Right here.

01:21:15.890 --> 01:21:17.190
&gt;&gt; Thank you, Ruth.

01:21:17.190 --> 01:21:19.340
I found this to be a very,
very stimulating discussion.

01:21:19.340 --> 01:21:25.680 position:56%
My question has to do with what your
views are on using amnesty as a way

01:21:25.680 --> 01:21:30.930
to bridge you know, some of the
shortcomings of the legislation.

01:21:30.930 --> 01:21:34.020
And perhaps including
also adjustments

01:21:34.020 --> 01:21:35.990
in the caps in the quotas.

01:21:35.990 --> 01:21:37.290
&gt;&gt; Ruth Wasem: One of
the things that struck me

01:21:37.290 --> 01:21:44.190
in my research was how frequently
in the past there were provisions.

01:21:44.190 --> 01:21:46.450 position:56%
Some called the registry provisions.

01:21:46.450 --> 01:21:49.960
Others were just -- they
just adjusted people,

01:21:49.960 --> 01:21:53.400
that today we would call
amnesty or legalization

01:21:53.400 --> 01:21:55.140
and it would be big news.

01:21:55.140 --> 01:21:57.050
But it happened all
through the '50's.

01:21:57.050 --> 01:22:01.640
And even Congressman Walter
of McCarran-Walter sponsored.

01:22:01.640 --> 01:22:04.350
You know, when I mentioned
some of the incremental bills,

01:22:04.350 --> 01:22:08.430 position:56%
one of them was an outright
legalization of certain populations.

01:22:08.430 --> 01:22:10.800
And you could just
come in and register.

01:22:10.800 --> 01:22:13.400
So those kinds of things weren't

01:22:13.400 --> 01:22:16.510
as controversial back
then as they are today.

01:22:16.510 --> 01:22:19.730
And I would love to
hear from my colleagues

01:22:19.730 --> 01:22:23.360
because I don't think
illegal presence was

01:22:23.360 --> 01:22:25.380
as stigmatized back then.

01:22:25.380 --> 01:22:28.890
Nor was it an illegal
concept then to be

01:22:28.890 --> 01:22:31.480 position:56%
in the United States without status.

01:22:31.480 --> 01:22:33.840
&gt;&gt; Marta Tienda: The
amnesty gets a lot of play

01:22:33.840 --> 01:22:36.800
when it's seen as a
national activity.

01:22:36.800 --> 01:22:38.100
We've been doing it.

01:22:38.100 --> 01:22:41.780
Congress has been doing
amnesties ever since '86.

01:22:41.780 --> 01:22:43.080
They do it on a rolling basis.

01:22:43.080 --> 01:22:46.330
Nacara. They've done this
population, that, so they do this.

01:22:46.330 --> 01:22:50.350 position:56%
There are all these little ones that
are done by congressional decision,

01:22:50.350 --> 01:22:51.650
but most people don't hear about it

01:22:51.650 --> 01:22:56.110
because it's not an
amnesty like a big amnesty.

01:22:56.110 --> 01:22:58.020
Therefore they're little
secrete amnesties.

01:22:58.020 --> 01:23:00.620
Those little amnesties
have added up to hundreds

01:23:00.620 --> 01:23:04.180
of thousands to date, since 1986.

01:23:04.180 --> 01:23:07.480
But because each one
is not like yes or no,

01:23:07.480 --> 01:23:09.360
the whole everybody who's here,

01:23:09.360 --> 01:23:12.410
it's a series of small
incremental changes.

01:23:12.410 --> 01:23:16.290
Of course the federal
government got sued

01:23:16.290 --> 01:23:21.070
for not handling systematically
the temporary protected status

01:23:21.070 --> 01:23:24.140
of individuals who were here

01:23:24.140 --> 01:23:27.050
as temporary workers,
refugees, et cetera.

01:23:27.050 --> 01:23:29.800
And they kept extending it.

01:23:29.800 --> 01:23:35.340
So they were systematically
allowing the Nicaraguans,

01:23:35.340 --> 01:23:38.790 position:56%
but not allowing the Guatemalans
and the Central Americans to qualify

01:23:38.790 --> 01:23:40.890
under the same conditions
until they were sued.

01:23:40.890 --> 01:23:45.330
Then they did retroactive
amnesty for many of them.

01:23:45.330 --> 01:23:47.240
But if we just go through,
there's a really nice paper

01:23:47.240 --> 01:23:49.920
by the Migration Policy Institute

01:23:49.920 --> 01:23:53.450
that documents how many
have been amnestied since.

01:23:53.450 --> 01:23:56.270 position:56%
I don't share the view of the author

01:23:56.270 --> 01:24:00.940
that it's greater than
the '86 amnesty.

01:24:00.940 --> 01:24:02.950
It's not, but that's the claim.

01:24:02.950 --> 01:24:06.860
But there have been
additional rolling additions

01:24:06.860 --> 01:24:11.910
to the initial amnesty where people
are grandfathered es post facto.

01:24:11.910 --> 01:24:14.200
But we're doing amnesty
all the time.

01:24:14.200 --> 01:24:16.570
We're just not drumrolling it.

01:24:16.570 --> 01:24:18.680
And it's the drumrolling
it in today's media

01:24:18.680 --> 01:24:21.870
and highly polarized environment
that Susan was talking about,

01:24:21.870 --> 01:24:24.820
that makes it seem like it's
out of line and out of course

01:24:24.820 --> 01:24:26.120
and like it's not what we're doing.

01:24:26.120 --> 01:24:27.460
They're doing it all the time.

01:24:27.460 --> 01:24:28.760
&gt;&gt; Ruth Wasem: Yeah.

01:24:28.760 --> 01:24:31.460
And getting I think to the
fundamentals of what you're asking,

01:24:31.460 --> 01:24:36.560
if you think about
fairness and equities

01:24:36.560 --> 01:24:41.630
as being what should drive
immigration policy, then it's hard

01:24:41.630 --> 01:24:46.560
to justify a situation where
11 million people are outside

01:24:46.560 --> 01:24:50.830
of that frame work and have
no ability to gain access

01:24:50.830 --> 01:24:57.330 position:56%
to legal status and/or an underclass
in a society which is built

01:24:57.330 --> 01:25:01.800
around bringing -- or should
be built around bringing people

01:25:01.800 --> 01:25:04.740
into the society rather
than excluding them.

01:25:04.740 --> 01:25:07.650
While often exploiting their labor.

01:25:07.650 --> 01:25:10.840
And so I think the country
at some point has to realize

01:25:10.840 --> 01:25:13.440
that it can't have its
cake and eat it too.

01:25:13.440 --> 01:25:17.160
That in fact this dependence
and you know,

01:25:17.160 --> 01:25:23.150 position:56%
kind of love of your own
undocumented gardener or housekeeper

01:25:23.150 --> 01:25:28.470
or you have a person working in the
Chinese restaurant that you go to

01:25:28.470 --> 01:25:32.850
or order from is fine, as long as
they're out of sight, out of mind

01:25:32.850 --> 01:25:36.600
and not legally here and
becoming part of our society.

01:25:36.600 --> 01:25:39.860
And I think, I want
to say one more thing

01:25:39.860 --> 01:25:41.640
and then I'll let him shut us down.

01:25:41.640 --> 01:25:44.520
And that is building
on the fairness, yes,

01:25:44.520 --> 01:25:47.340
there is the fairness question

01:25:47.340 --> 01:25:50.510
of how we treat unauthorized
aliens who are currently here.

01:25:50.510 --> 01:25:53.310
But we also have -- and I'm
looking at my colleague William --

01:25:53.310 --> 01:25:59.360
we have 4 million approved
petitions of relatives

01:25:59.360 --> 01:26:01.340
who are waiting to come in.

01:26:01.340 --> 01:26:05.800
And they're waiting, and
how gets to go first?

01:26:05.800 --> 01:26:07.540
Who gets the green card first?

01:26:07.540 --> 01:26:08.980
What is fair?

01:26:08.980 --> 01:26:10.720
The brother and sister?

01:26:10.720 --> 01:26:12.340
Because we've put that
in the priorities.

01:26:12.340 --> 01:26:16.640
And the parents, the people
that are waiting to come in,

01:26:16.640 --> 01:26:19.300
what is the fairest way to do this?

01:26:19.300 --> 01:26:22.250
And I think that these are
pretty tough questions.

01:26:22.250 --> 01:26:25.030
&gt;&gt; Susan Martin: And they're aging
